Appendix B: Computational Resources and Algorithms

B.1 Lattice QCD Computational Scaling

Memory Requirements:
For SU(3) lattice of size L¬≥√óT:

¬∑ Gauge fields: 4 √ó 3¬≤ √ó 2 √ó 8 bytes √ó L¬≥T (real and imaginary parts)
¬∑ Example: 64‚Å¥ lattice: 4√ó9√ó2√ó8√ó64‚Å¥ ‚âà 7.5 GB
¬∑ 256‚Å¥ lattice: ~7.5√ó256 = 1.9 TB (compression possible)

Compute Requirements (Monte Carlo):
One HMC trajectory requires:

¬∑ Force calculation: O(V) flops
¬∑ Matrix inversions (for fermions): O(V¬≥) without improvements, O(V log V) with multigrid
¬∑ Typical: 10‚Å∂ flops/site √ó 10‚Åµ sites = 10¬π¬π flops per trajectory

Autocorrelation Times:
For topological charge: œÑ_int ‚àº e^{c/Œ≤} (critical slowing down)
For glueball correlators: œÑ_int ‚àº 10-100 trajectories

Extrapolation to Continuum:
Need multiple lattice spacings a for fit:

m(a) = m_0 + c_1 a + c_2 a¬≤ + ...

Typically need 4-5 different a values.

B.2 Hybrid Monte Carlo Algorithm

Algorithm B.2.1 (HMC for Pure Gauge):

```
Input: Œ≤, lattice size, trajectory length œÑ, step size Œµ
Initialize: U randomly or from previous configuration

for i = 1 to N_configs:
    # Generate conjugate momenta
    P = random Gaussian with ‚ü®P¬≤‚ü© = 1
    
    # Molecular dynamics
    U' = U, P' = P
    H_initial = S[U'] + ¬Ω‚àë P'¬≤
    
    for t = 1 to œÑ/Œµ:
        P' = P' - (Œµ/2) * Œ¥S/Œ¥U(U')  # half step
        U' = exp(iŒµP') * U'           # full step
        P' = P' - (Œµ/2) * Œ¥S/Œ¥U(U')  # half step
    
    H_final = S[U'] + ¬Ω‚àë P'¬≤
    ŒîH = H_final - H_initial
    
    # Metropolis accept/reject
    if random(0,1) < exp(-ŒîH):
        U = U'  # accept
    else:
        keep U   # reject
    
    if i > N_thermalize:
        measure observables
```

Force Calculation:

\frac{Œ¥S_W}{Œ¥U_Œº(x)} = -Œ≤ ‚àë_{ŒΩ‚â†Œº} \left[ U_ŒΩ(x)U_Œº(x+ŒΩÃÇ)U_ŒΩ^\dagger(x+ŒºÃÇ) + U_ŒΩ^\dagger(x-ŒΩÃÇ)U_Œº(x-ŒΩÃÇ)U_ŒΩ(x-ŒΩÃÇ+ŒºÃÇ) \right]_{\text{traceless}}

B.3 Quantum Computing for Yang-Mills

Qubit Requirements:
For SU(2) on N_s sites:

¬∑ Kogut-Susskind formulation: 3 qubits per link (for j=1/2 representation)
¬∑ Digital encoding: log‚ÇÇ(dim ‚Ñã) qubits for entire Hilbert space
¬∑ Example: 2√ó2√ó2 lattice: ~1000 qubits for full Hilbert space

Algorithm B.3.1 (Quantum Simulation of Time Evolution):

```
# Using Trotter decomposition
U(t) = e^{-iHt} ‚âà (e^{-iH_1 t/n} e^{-iH_2 t/n})^n

where H = H_E + H_B:
H_E = g¬≤/2 ‚àë E¬≤  (electric part)
H_B = 1/(2g¬≤) ‚àë (2 - U_P - U_P^\dagger)  (magnetic part)

# Circuit for e^{-iH_E Œît}:
for each link ‚Ñì:
    apply R_z(Œ∏) rotation to qubits, Œ∏ = g¬≤Œît

# Circuit for e^{-iH_B Œît}:
for each plaquette P:
    implement controlled rotations based on
    product of U's around plaquette
```

Error Correction Requirements:
Surface code: distance d code requires ~2d¬≤ physical qubits per logical qubit.
For 100 logical qubits with d=11: ~24,000 physical qubits.

