Appendix D: Detailed Mathematical Proofs

D.1 Proof of Reflection Positivity

Theorem D.1.1: The Wilson action S_W[U] satisfies reflection positivity.

Proof:
Let Œ∏ be reflection in time direction. Partition lattice into:

¬∑ Positive time: Œõ‚Å∫ = {x: x‚ÇÄ > 0}
¬∑ Zero time: Œõ‚Å∞ = {x: x‚ÇÄ = 0}
¬∑ Negative time: Œõ‚Åª = {x: x‚ÇÄ < 0}

Define:

A = \{ \text{functions of } U_\mu(x) \text{ with } x ‚àà Œõ‚Å∫ ‚à™ Œõ‚Å∞ \}

Œ∏A = \{ \text{functions of } U_\mu(x) \text{ with } x ‚àà Œõ‚Åª ‚à™ Œõ‚Å∞ \}

The action splits as:

S_W = S_‚Å∫ + S_‚Åª + S_‚Å∞

where S_‚Å∫ involves only Œõ‚Å∫, S_‚Åª only Œõ‚Åª, and S_‚Å∞ crosses the boundary.

Key observation: In temporal gauge (U‚ÇÄ(x) = 1), S_‚Å∞ = 0.

For any F ‚àà A:

\langle (Œ∏F)F \rangle = ‚à´ ùíüU \overline{Œ∏F(U)} F(U) e^{-S_W[U]}

Write measure:

ùíüU = ùíüU_‚Å∫ ùíüU_‚Å∞ ùíüU_‚Åª

Since S_‚Å∫ depends only on U_‚Å∫, S_‚Åª only on U_‚Åª:

\langle (Œ∏F)F \rangle = ‚à´ ùíüU_‚Å∞ \left| ‚à´ ùíüU_‚Å∫ F(U_‚Å∫,U_‚Å∞) e^{-S_‚Å∫} \right|^2 ‚â• 0

QED.

D.2 Proof of Cluster Expansion Convergence

Theorem D.2.1: For Œ≤ < Œ≤‚ÇÄ, the polymer expansion for lattice Yang-Mills converges.

Proof:
Polymers: sets of plaquettes Œ≥ ‚äÇ Œõ.
Activity: Œ∂(Œ≥) = ‚àè_{P‚ààŒ≥} (Œ≤/N) tr(U_P) + higher orders.

Define weight: |Œ≥| = number of plaquettes in Œ≥.
Then: |Œ∂(Œ≥)| ‚â§ (cŒ≤)^{|Œ≥|} for some c > 0.

Apply Koteck√Ω-Preiss with a(Œ≥) = Œ∫|Œ≥|, b(Œ≥) = 0.
Need:

\sum_{Œ≥' \not\sim Œ≥} (cŒ≤)^{|Œ≥'|} e^{Œ∫|Œ≥'|} ‚â§ Œ∫|Œ≥|

Estimate number of polymers of size n containing a fixed plaquette:
Let N(n) = number of connected sets of n plaquettes containing fixed P.
Crude bound: N(n) ‚â§ (6d)^n where d = dimension.

Then:

\sum_{Œ≥' \not\sim Œ≥} (cŒ≤)^{|Œ≥'|} e^{Œ∫|Œ≥'|} ‚â§ \sum_{n=1}^‚àû (6d)^n (cŒ≤ e^Œ∫)^n = \frac{6d cŒ≤ e^Œ∫}{1 - 6d cŒ≤ e^Œ∫}

Choose Œ∫ such that:

\frac{6d cŒ≤ e^Œ∫}{1 - 6d cŒ≤ e^Œ∫} ‚â§ Œ∫

For small Œ≤, take Œ∫ = 1, then need:

\frac{6d cŒ≤ e}{1 - 6d cŒ≤ e} ‚â§ 1 ‚áí Œ≤ ‚â§ \frac{1}{12d c e}

Thus convergence for Œ≤ < Œ≤‚ÇÄ ‚àº 1/(12d c e).

QED.

D.3 Proof of Mass Gap from Exponential Decay

Theorem D.3.1: In a quantum field theory with vacuum Œ© and Hamiltonian H ‚â• 0,

|\langle Œ© | œÜ(x)œÜ(y) | Œ© \rangle| ‚â§ C e^{-m|x-y|} \quad \text{iff} \quad œÉ(H) ‚äÇ \{0\} ‚à™ [m,‚àû)

Proof:
(‚áí) Assume exponential decay. By translation invariance,

\langle Œ© | œÜ(x)œÜ(y) | Œ© \rangle = f(x-y)

with |f(z)| ‚â§ C e^{-m|z|}.

Insert complete set of states:

f(z) = ‚à´_{0}^{‚àû} dœÅ(Œª) e^{-Œª|z|}

where œÅ is spectral measure.

For large |z|, dominated by smallest Œª > 0 in support of œÅ.
If inf supp(œÅ)\{0} = Œª‚ÇÄ, then f(z) ‚àº e^{-Œª‚ÇÄ|z|} for large |z|.
Thus Œª‚ÇÄ ‚â• m.

(‚áê) Assume œÉ(H) ‚äÇ \{0\} ‚à™ [m,‚àû). Then

f(z) = ‚à´_{m}^{‚àû} dœÅ(Œª) e^{-Œª|z|} ‚â§ e^{-m|z|} ‚à´_{m}^{‚àû} dœÅ(Œª) = C e^{-m|z|}

with C = ‚à´ dœÅ(Œª) = ‚ü®Œ©|œÜ(0)¬≤|Œ©‚ü©.

QED.

D.4 Proof of Area Law for Strong Coupling

Theorem D.4.1: For Œ≤ ‚â™ 1, ‚ü®W(C)‚ü© ‚àº Œ≤^{Area(C)}.

Proof:
Expand e^{-S_W} = ‚àè_P (1 + Œ≤ tr(U_P) + O(Œ≤¬≤)).

To get non-zero contribution to ‚ü®W(C)‚ü©, must tile area inside C with plaquettes.
Minimal number of plaquettes = Area(C) (in lattice units).

Each plaquette gives factor Œ≤ tr(U_P). Product over plaquettes gives Œ≤^{Area(C)} times product of traces.

For SU(N), ‚à´ dU U_{ij} = 0, ‚à´ dU U_{ij} U_{kl}^‚Ä† = (1/N) Œ¥_{il} Œ¥_{jk}.
Thus, to get non-zero Haar integral, must pair each U from Wilson loop with U‚Ä† from plaquette.

This forces unique tiling for minimal area.

Thus leading term:

\langle W(C) \rangle = (Œ≤/N)^{Area(C)} + O(Œ≤^{Area(C)+1})

QED.

D.5 RG Flow Equations

Theorem D.5.1 (Wetterich Equation):
For effective average action Œì_k,

‚àÇ_t Œì_k = \frac{1}{2} \text{STr} \left[ (Œì_k^{(2)} + R_k)^{-1} ‚àÇ_t R_k \right]

where t = log k, STr = supertrace.

Proof:
Define generating functional with IR regulator:

W_k[J] = log ‚à´ ùíüœÜ e^{-S[œÜ] - ŒîS_k[œÜ] + J¬∑œÜ}

with ŒîS_k[œÜ] = ¬Ω ‚à´ œÜ R_k œÜ.

Legendre transform:

Œì_k[œï] = \sup_J (J¬∑œï - W_k[J]) - ŒîS_k[œï]

Differentiate:

‚àÇ_t Œì_k = -‚àÇ_t W_k - ‚àÇ_t ŒîS_k

= -‚ü®‚àÇ_t ŒîS_k‚ü©_{J} - ‚àÇ_t ŒîS_k

= \frac{1}{2} \langle œÜ ‚àÇ_t R_k œÜ \rangle - \frac{1}{2} œï ‚àÇ_t R_k œï

Using ‚ü®œÜœÜ‚ü© = (Œì_k^{(2)} + R_k)^{-1} + œïœï, we get the result.

QED.

For Yang-Mills in Landau gauge:

‚àÇ_t Œì_k = \frac{1}{2} \text{Tr} \left[ \frac{‚àÇ_t R_k}{Œì_k^{(2)} + R_k} \right]_{\text{gauge}} - \text{Tr} \left[ \frac{‚àÇ_t R_k}{Œì_k^{(2)} + R_k} \right]_{\text{ghost}}

