Appendix E: Historical Context and Bibliography

E.1 Timeline of Key Developments

1954: Yang & Mills publish "Conservation of Isotopic Spin and Isotopic Gauge Invariance"

1971: 't Hooft proves renormalizability of non-abelian gauge theories

1973: Wilson introduces lattice gauge theory; Gross, Wilczek, Politzer discover asymptotic freedom

1974: Osterwalder & Schrader prove reconstruction theorem

1975: Callan, Gross, Wilczek compute Œ≤-function to two loops

1979: Creutz publishes first Monte Carlo simulations of lattice gauge theory

1982: Witten proves mass gap for 2D Yang-Mills

1983: Glimm & Jaffe publish "Quantum Physics: A Functional Integral Point of View"

1994: Seiberg & Witten solve N=2 supersymmetric Yang-Mills

1998: Maldacena proposes AdS/CFT correspondence

2000: Clay Institute announces Millennium Prize problems

2006: Luscher publishes "Computational Strategies in Lattice QCD"

2012: ATLAS/CMS discover Higgs boson (Yang-Mills with spontaneous symmetry breaking)

2020: Exascale computing initiatives begin worldwide

2025: Projected completion of first exascale lattice calculations

